summary.body:
An experiment was performed to assess the precision of the Gamma Glutamyl Transferase on the Abbott Alininity i from Abbott. 2 levels were  in a total of 10 runs with 50 measurements. 
This experiment used Total Allowable Errors from RCPA. with a within run and within day error allowance of 35% and a between day error allowance of 50%. 
Based on the precision acceptance criterias for this verification, requirements to verify the precision of the Gamma Glutamyl Transferase test were verified.

description.body: Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is an enzyme that is found in many organs throughout the body, with the highest concentrations found in the liver. GGT is elevated in the blood in most diseases that cause damage to the liver or bile ducts. This test measures the level of GGT in a blood sample.

summary.body:
An experiment was performed to assess the linearity of the Gamma Glutamyl Transferase on the Abbott Alininity i from Abbott. 5 levels were plotted with a total of 59 (minimum: 3 per level). A linear regression analysis was performed and produced an R-Squared value of 1 with a slope and intercept of: y = 1x + 1.035.The method's test range of 0-500 g/dLwas evaluated and an analytical measurement range (AMR) of  - 500 g/dL with a linear extension of 8%.
Based on the results of this experiment, the linearity and AMR of the Gamma Glutamyl Transferase on the Abbott was  verified.

description.body: A protein in urine test measures how much protein is in your urine. Proteins are substances that are essential for your body to function properly. Protein is normally found in the blood. If there is a problem with your kidneys, protein can leak into your urine. While a small amount is normal, a large amount of protein in urine may indicate kidney disease.
